# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asia-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] The **1984 Asia Cup** (also known as the **Rothmans Asia Cup**) was the inaugural edition of the Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] It was held in Sharjah, UAE, which was the location of the newly formed Asian Cricket Council.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] The new tournament was held between April 6–13, in 1984 and three teams took part: India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] The Sharjah Cricket Association Stadium hosted its first One Day International (ODI) match.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] The 1984 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] India won both its matches, winning the inaugural Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1984-asia-cup] Sri Lanka came in second while Pakistan lost both its matches.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The **1986 Asia Cup** (also known as the **John Player Asia Cup 86**) was the second Asia Cup tournament, and was held in Sri Lanka between March 30 and April 6.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] Three teams took part in the tournament: Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Asian leading associate member Bangladesh.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] India pulled out of the tournament due to strained cricketing relations with Sri Lanka and was replaced by Asian leading associate nation Bangladesh, which had qualified by winning the 1984 South-East Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The 1986 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] Pakistan won both its matches and qualified for the final against Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] Sri Lanka beat Pakistan to win their first Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The First South-East Asian Cricket Tournament was held in Dhaka in January 1984.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] Two teams from the host country were joined by teams from Singapore and Hong Kong.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The Bangladesh national team won the trophy, and thus qualified for the 1986 Asia Cup in Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The organizers suffered an early setback when Malaysia, one of the stronger cricketing nations of the Far East, withdrew at the last moment.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] Apart from Dhaka, Chittagong and Mymensingh hosted some games.
[src:asia-cup/1984-south-east-asia-cup] The Bangladesh national team, however, played all its fixtures at the capital.
[src:asia-cup/1988-asia-cup] The **1988 Asia Cup** (also known as the **Wills Asia Cup**) was the third Asia Cup tournament, held in Bangladesh between 26 October and 4 November 1988.
[src:asia-cup/1988-asia-cup] Four teams took part in the tournament: India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and the host nation Bangladesh.
[src:asia-cup/1988-asia-cup] The matches were the first-ever List A-classified being played in Bangladesh, then an Associate Member of the International Cricket Council (ICC), their opponents all being Full Members.
[src:asia-cup/1988-asia-cup] The 1988 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other three once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1988-asia-cup] India and Sri Lanka qualified for the final in which India defeated Sri Lanka by 6 wickets to win its second Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1990-91-asia-cup] The **1990–91 Asia Cup** was the fourth Asia Cup tournament, and was held in India between 25 December 1990, and 4 January 1991.
[src:asia-cup/1990-91-asia-cup] Three teams took part in the tournament: India, Sri Lanka and Asian leading associate member Bangladesh.
[src:asia-cup/1990-91-asia-cup] Pakistan had pulled out of the tournament due to strained political relations with India.
[src:asia-cup/1990-91-asia-cup] The 1990–91 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1990-91-asia-cup] India and Sri Lanka qualified for the final in which India beat Sri Lanka by 7 wickets to win its second consecutive (and third in total) Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The **Men's Asia Cup** is a biennial cricket tournament organized by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] It features senior men's national teams from Asian member countries and determines the continental cricket champion of Asia.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The tournament was established in the year 1983, coinciding with the formation of the Asian Cricket Council, as an effort to promote goodwill among Asian countries through cricket.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India boycotted the 1986 edition due to strained cricketing relations with Sri Lanka, while Pakistan withdrew from the 1990–91 edition because of political tensions with India.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The 1993 tournament was also cancelled for similar reasons.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The ACC later announced that the event would be held biennially starting from 2009.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The ICC recognizes all Asia Cup matches as official ODI games.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] After downsizing the Asian Cricket Council in 2015, it was announced by the ICC that Asia Cup events from 2016 would be played on a rotation basis between One Day International and Twenty20 International format, on the basis of the format of upcoming world events.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] As a result, the 2016 event was the first event played in the T20I format and functioned as a preparatory tournament ahead of the 2016 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India, with nine titles (seven ODI and two T20I), is the most successful team in the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka is the second most successful team with six titles (five ODI and one T20I), while Pakistan have won two.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka has participated in the most Asia Cups (17), followed by India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh (16 each).
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The inaugural edition of the Rothmans Asia Cup took place in Sharjah, UAE, in 1984, coinciding with the establishment of the Asian Cricket Council headquartered in the same city.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The event featured a round-robin format between India, Sri Lanka, and Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India won both its matches to claim the first title, while Sri Lanka finished second after defeating Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka hosted the second edition in 1986.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India withdrew from the tournament due to strained cricketing relations with Sri Lanka after a controversial series the previous year.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Bangladesh participated for the first time.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka won the tournament by defeating Pakistan in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The third edition, in 1988, was held in Bangladesh, marking the first time a multi-national cricket tournament was staged there.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] In the final, India beat Sri Lanka by six wickets to claim their second Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The fourth edition of the tournament was held in India in 1990–91.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan withdrew because of strained political relations with India.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India retained the Asia Cup by defeating Sri Lanka in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] In 1993, the tournament was cancelled due to continued political tensions between India and Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The fifth edition, in 1995, returned to Sharjah, UAE after eleven years.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India and Sri Lanka reached the final by virtue of a superior run rate over Pakistan, as all three teams finished the preliminary round with equal points.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] For the third successive time, India defeated Sri Lanka in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The sixth edition was held in Sri Lanka in 1997, where the hosts beat India in the final by eight wickets to win their second Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The seventh edition of the Asia Cup was held in Bangladesh in 2000, marking the second time the country hosted the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan and Sri Lanka reached the final, while India won only one match (against Bangladesh) and, for the first time, failed to qualify for the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan defeated Sri Lanka to win their maiden Asia Cup title, with Yousuf Youhana named Player of the Tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The 8th edition took place in Sri Lanka in 2004 with a new format.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] UAE and Hong Kong joined the competition for the first time, making it a six-team event divided into three stages – Group Stage, Super Fours, and the Final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka, India, and UAE were placed in Group A, while Pakistan, Bangladesh, and Hong Kong were in Group B.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] UAE and Hong Kong were eliminated in the group stage.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Bangladesh progressed to the Super Fours for the first time in a major tournament but failed to perform.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India and Sri Lanka topped the Super Fours to reach the final, where Sri Lanka defeated India by 25 runs.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sanath Jayasuriya was awarded Player of the Tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The 9th edition was hosted by Pakistan from 24 June to 6 July 2008, following the same format as 2004.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka and Bangladesh qualified from Group A, while India and Pakistan advanced from Group B.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] In the Super Fours, India and Sri Lanka finished on top to enter the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka won their fourth Asia Cup by defeating India by 100 runs.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sanath Jayasuriya scored 125 off 114 balls to rescue Sri Lanka from 66/4, while mystery spinner Ajantha Mendis produced a match-winning spell of 6/13.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Mendis was named Player of the Tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The tenth edition was held in Sri Lanka, between 15 and 24 June 2010 hosting the Asia Cup for the fourth time.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] It only featured the four Test playing Asian nations, and seven matches were played in all (including the final).
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka and India topped the group stages and entered the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] In the final, India beat Sri Lanka comfortably to become champions for the fifth time, winning the tournament for first time in 15 years.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Shahid Afridi was the Player of the Tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The eleventh edition of the Asia Cup was held in Dhaka, Bangladesh, from 11 to 22 March 2012.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan and Bangladesh qualified to play in the final of the eleventh edition, Bangladesh had beaten India and Sri Lanka to book their place in the final for the first time in the history of the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan beat Bangladesh after a thrilling final over, winning their second Asia Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Shakib Al Hasan was adjudged the Player of the Tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sachin Tendulkar scored his 100th international century in this tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The twelfth edition was held in Dhaka and Fatullah, Bangladesh, from 25 February to 8 March 2014.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The tournament consisted of five teams with Afghanistan in it for the first time since its inception in 1984.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka defeated Pakistan by 5 wickets in the final to win the Asia Cup for the fifth time.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Lahiru Thirimanne was adjudged the Player of the Tournament scoring 279 runs.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] After the Asian Cricket Council was downsized by the ICC in 2015, it was announced that Asia Cup tournaments would be played on rotation basis in ODI and T20I format.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] As a result, 2016 events was the first tournament in T20I format and was played by five teams just ahead of 2016 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The 2016 edition of the Asia Cup tournament was held in Bangladesh for the third consecutive time from 24 February to 6 March.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India won the final by beating Bangladesh by 8 wickets in the final held at the Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium situated in Mirpur locality, Dhaka, Bangladesh.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] It is for the sixth time that India won the Asia cup title in 2016.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Shikhar Dhawan of India was the man of the match for his 60 runs.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sabbir Rahman of Bangladesh was the player of the series.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India won all of its matches played in Asia Cup 2016 beating Bangladesh 2 times, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and UAE.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] On 29 October 2015, following the Asian Cricket Council meeting in Singapore, BCCI secretary Anurag Thakur stated that the 2018 edition of the tournament would be held in India.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] However, in April 2018, the tournament was moved to the United Arab Emirates, due to political tensions between India and Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India were the defending champions, and retained their title, after beating Bangladesh by three wickets in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India did not suffer a single defeat in the tournament, with 2 wins each against Pakistan & Bangladesh, a solitary win against Hong Kong, and a tie with Afghanistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Shikhar Dhawan was the top run getter with 342 runs in 5 matches, was awarded Man of the Series.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Afghanistan was the only team in the tournament who remained unbeaten against eventual winners India.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The United Arab Emirates hosted the tournament and Sri Lanka won the Asia Cup beating Pakistan by 23 runs in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Sri Lanka reached the final as the only unbeaten team in the Super-Four stage winning against Afghanistan, India, and Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Bhanuka Rajapaksa was awarded Man of the Match for his unbeaten 71 off 45 balls, and Wanindu Hasaranga was second highest wicket-taker with 9 wickets in 6 matches, scored 66 runs in 5 innings and was named Player of the Series.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan had an average start in the Asia Cup with a defeat against India in the group stage, beating India & Afghanistan in a close encounter in Super 4, ending with 2 back-to-back defeats against Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India started the tournament as hot favourites defeating Pakistan; however, they could not win against them and Sri Lanka in the super 4 and got knocked out of the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Afghanistan was the only team in the tournament to defeat the eventual winners Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Pakistan was awarded to host the tournament in 2023.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] However, the Indian cricket team was reluctant to visit Pakistan to participate in the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] So, after a lot of deliberation, India agreed to play in a hybrid model where India will play all their matches in another country and few other matches will be hosted in Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Thus, it was the first Asia Cup to be co-hosted by multiple countries; four matches were played in Pakistan, and the remaining nine matches were played in Sri Lanka.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The five full members of the Asian Cricket Council were joined by Nepal, who made their ACC Asia Cup debut having qualified for the first time in qualifying the 2023 ACC Men's Premier Cup.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and Afghanistan qualified to play in the tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, and Sri Lanka qualified to play the Super fours stage.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] India and Pakistan played the finals, in which India defeated Pakistan by 5 wickets to win their ninth Asia cup title.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] Around 80% of the tournament's revenue is generated from matches featuring India and Pakistan.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] To meet broadcasting demands, the two teams are often placed in the same group for commercial reasons.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The five Full Members each receive approximately 15% of total revenue, with the remaining amount distributed among Associate and Affiliate national boards.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The BCCI has publicly stated that it donates a portion of its share to smaller boards to support cricket development within and outside Asia.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The table below provides an overview of the performances of teams over past Asia Cup ODI and T20I tournaments.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The table below provides an overview of the performances of teams over past Asia Cup ODI tournaments.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] The table below provides an overview of the performances of teams in the Asia Cup T20I tournament.
[src:asia-cup/1993-asia-cup] 9, while Sri Lanka has second highest 6.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] The **1995 Asia Cup** (also known as the **Pepsi Asia Cup**), was the fifth Asia Cup tournament, and the second to be held in Sharjah, UAE.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] The tournament took place between April 5–14, 1995.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] Four teams took part in the tournament: India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] The 1995 Asia Cup was a round-robin tournament where each team played the other once, and the top two teams qualifying for a place in the final.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] All the matches, including the final, were played at the Sharjah Cricket Association Stadium in Sharjah.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka all had four points at the end of the round-robin stage, but India and Sri Lanka qualified for the final on the basis of better run-rates.
[src:asia-cup/1995-asia-cup] India beat Sri Lanka by 8 wickets to win its third consecutive (and fourth in total) Asia Cup.
